Parses `dict.steno`'s raw source text (not its parsed dictionary structure) for two kinds of human-authored annotations: `## label` category markers and `### text` description markers, so the viz tool can group and annotate dictionary entries without those markers being real steno-dictionary syntax.

The key distinction: a `## label` line sets the *current category* for every subsequent entry until the next `## ` line — it's a running state, not a per-entry tag (`label_for` finds the nearest preceding marker, defaulting to `"Uncategorized"`). A `### text` line, by contrast, describes only the *single* fenced entry immediately following it; blank lines between the marker and the fence are tolerated, but any other intervening line (including another marker or unrelated text) clears the pending description before it attaches to anything. `marker_label` explicitly rejects lines starting with `###` so the two marker kinds don't collide when scanning for `##`.

Fence detection (`is_fence_open`) requires exactly four backticks followed by non-empty content, distinguishing an opening fence (with trailing stroke text) from a bare closing fence — this must stay consistent with however `dict.steno`'s entries are actually fenced elsewhere in the viz_data pipeline, since this file has no knowledge of the fence's closing counterpart or nesting.

Public API: `scan(src: &str) -> Vec<Marker>` (each `Marker` has 1-based `line` and trimmed `label`, in file order), `label_for(markers: &[Marker], entry_line: usize) -> &str`, and `scan_desc(src: &str) -> HashMap<usize, String>` mapping a fence's 1-based opening line number to its trimmed description text. All line numbers are 1-based throughout, matching typical editor/source conventions — callers passing 0-based indices will get wrong results silently.